content.problemStatement:
An `infinite loop` is a loop that never stops running because its condition is always `true`. This can happen by accident - like forgetting to update a variable or on purpose - such as in programs that must keep running, like games, servers, or waiting for user input.

**Syntax:**

**1. Deliberate Infinite Loop (Condition always true)**
```cpp
while (true) {
    // Code that runs endlessly
}
```
**2. Accidental Infinite Loop (Missing update)**
```cpp
datatype variable_name = initial_value;

while (variable_name 
using namespace std;

int main() {

    // First: Deliberate infinite loop (condition always true)
    while (true) {
        cout << "This will run forever (true condition)\n" << endl;
        break;  // Added to stop it after one run for demo
    }

    // Second: Accidental infinite loop (missing update)
    int i = 1;
    while (i <= 3) {
        cout << "This will also run forever (i is never updated)" << endl;
        // i++;  // Intentionally left out
    }

    return 0;
}

```
**Expected Output:**
```default
This will run forever (true condition)

This will also run forever (i is never updated)
This will also run forever (i is never updated)
This will also run forever (i is never updated)
...and so on
```

